description: Land Surveyors United (LSU) is the first social network in the world exclusively geared for land surveying professionals and the GPS, mapping and geomatics community. This network creates a portable, local, virtual space for surveyors to post their technology related questions, experiences, tips, tricks and advise for the field. Our 'members only' network is a mobile social support system designed to help the common surveyor accomplish daily tasks much quicker, having access to the global support of peers and collegues. Tell us a surveying story and I promise you'll get one back in return.

properties.name: timothy paul bell
properties.description: I started as a rodman cutting tall corn in September of 1970 for DeLuew/Cather along the centerline of I-88 in northern IL. We hubbed and tacked every 100' of 4 miles to check/find original PIs, POTs, PCs, & PTs. Our crews were shot at and crop-dusted and I thought; what a cool job! I knew nothing of surveying; I actually thought it was a dead profession. Now, 40 years later, I wonder if it is or not. I continued to work for numerous engineering firms for 8 years. Then, I went to Ferris State College in Big Rapids, MI and got a 4 year BS in Surveying - that was May of 1981. Then I moved to MN, got licensed in MN, IL & SD. Did three Cadastral contracts in the Black Hills - exciting b/c we found original PLSS corners and Bearing Trees. We busted 10 sections around MT. Rushmore, really cool. Then with my own survey business, we did GPS jobs in MN winter around CASS Lake & Black Duck - snowmobiles, northern lights and logging trucks! Also in Red Wing along the high bluffs of the Mississippi; in Minneapolis duriing the great solar event of 1989; in Mankato; and in Northfield. I started doing GPS in 1987 and the first to use 5 Ashtechs and 4 Trimble 4000SDs simulltaneously in observation - what a nightmare! Now I'm back in IL, my home State, sitting here unemployed and writing this. I'm 57 but feel I've still got something to prove in surveying -- it's my life and in my blood. I'm not dead yet!Zoom in!
